    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_10910142" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/10910142" />
    <a title="Demetria" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/295381-demetria"><img alt="Demetria" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1194198683p2/295381.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/10910142?book_show_action=true">Dec 23, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Demetria" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Demetria" href="/user/show/295381-demetria">Demetria</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">writers</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer10910142" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8017098691581993044">I&apos;m usually not too keen on books that are allegedly for writers, but this one is really good. Francine Prose (gotta love the name) does an excellent job of utilizing literary works and her own experiences to illustrate points without being too textbooky. There are chapters on things like word choice, sentence structure and dialogue, but I swear it&apos;s interesting! There&apos;s also a pretty handy list at the end, of books that illustrate some of the points Prose makes. This book has actually made me b</span>
  <span id="freeText8017098691581993044" style="display:none">I'm usually not too keen on books that are allegedly for writers, but this one is really good. Francine Prose (gotta love the name) does an excellent job of utilizing literary works and her own experiences to illustrate points without being too textbooky. There are chapters on things like word choice, sentence structure and dialogue, but I swear it's interesting! There's also a pretty handy list at the end, of books that illustrate some of the points Prose makes. This book has actually made me be a little more academic when I'm reading. I'm back to highlighting things and taking notes. This is a great book for writers. </span>
  <a data-text-id="8017098691581993044" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

